Sure! Below is a complete HTML file that creates a simple A-Frame VR Mario clone. The player can navigate using the arrow keys, and the sprite face images are sourced from `https://picsum.photos/200/300`.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>A-Frame VR Mario Clone</title>
    <script src="https://aframe.io/releases/1.2.0/aframe.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            overflow: hidden;
        }

        #game {
            position: absolute;
            top: 0;
            left: 0;
            width: 100%;
            height: 100%;
        }

        .sprite {
            width: 200px;
            height: 300px;
            position: absolute;
            bottom: 0;
            left: 50%;
            transform: translateX(-50%);
        }
    </style>
</head>

<body>
    <div id="game">
        <a-scene>
            <a-sky color="#87CEEB"></a-sky>
            <a-box position="-1 0.5 -3" rotation="0 45 0" color="#4CC3D2"></a-box>
            <a-sphere position="1 1 -3" radius="1.25" color="#EF2D5E"></a-sphere>
            <a-cylinder position="0 0.75 -3" radius="0.5" height="1.5" color="#FFC65D"></a-cylinder>
            <a-plane position="0 0 -4" rotation="-90 0 0" width="4" height="4" color="#7BC8A4"></a-plane>
            <a-entity id="player" position="0 1.6 0" camera look-controls></a-entity>
        </a-scene>
        <img class="sprite" id="sprite" src="https://picsum.photos/200/300" alt="Mario Sprite">
    </div>

    <script>
        const player = document.getElementById('player');
        const sprite = document.getElementById('sprite');
        let position = { x: 0, y: 1.6, z: 0 };

        document.addEventListener('keydown', (event) => {
            switch (event.key) {
                case 'ArrowUp':
                    position.z -= 0.1;
                    break;
                case 'ArrowDown':
                    position.z += 0.1;
                    break;
                case 'ArrowLeft':
                    position.x -= 0.1;
                    break;
                case 'ArrowRight':
                    position.x += 0.1;
                    break;
            }
            player.setAttribute('position', position);
            sprite.style.transform = `translateX(${position.x * 100}px)`;
        });
    </script>
</body>

</html>
```

**Explanation:**

- **HTML Structure**: The document includes a basic structure with a title and a scene for A-Frame.

- **A-Frame Scene**: The scene contains a sky, some basic shapes (box, sphere, cylinder, and plane) to represent the environment.

- **Sprite Image**: The image of the sprite is displayed at the bottom of the screen, sourced from `https://picsum.photos/200/300`.

- **Navigation**: The arrow keys are used to navigate the player entity in the VR environment. The sprite's position is updated based on the player's movement.

You can copy and paste this code into an HTML file and open it in a web browser to see the VR Mario clone in action!
